SampleComment: GPS: 53.49764. -112.97970. Wind Speed: 30 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.01 m. Lots of rain night before and morning of sampling. Was raining and then stopped once profile sampling commenced. Lot of submerged aquatic macrophtes - milfoil looking. Grass clipping type algal colonies suspended in the water (aphanizomenon sp.?). Wind speed fluctuated throughout sampling. Coots nested in the reeds + island. Composited of hand grab samples. -- Microcystin ID M190203. Meter Number 60451. Wisconsin Net

GPS: 53.49761. -112.97894. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.01 m. Overcast but relatively calm day. Cyanobacterial bloom worse today. Visible colonies are Aphanizomenon, but other species certainly blooming as well. Many more macrophyte patches throughot the lake, primarily coontial. Milfoil collected from south portion of the lake, but in very low abundance. AIS mussel veliger samples were  collected via a tow method. Micocystin ID M190204. Probe 60451. Tow Net.

GPS: 53.49784, -112.98457. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: SE. Waves: 0.05 m. Ducks (Leah said Geese and swans sometimes). Very few people use the lake. No power boats allowed. No fish in the lake. Dessicated algae - blue. Grass clippings. Veg in clumps. Either tons of veg or no veg. DO @ 1.5 highly unstable (fluctuated 140% to 70%. Microcystin ID M190205. Probe 60443. Tow Net.

GPS: 53.49764. -112.97970. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.01 m. Very cold today. Started snowing during sampling. Water was very brown, and macrophytes (primarily milfoil and coontail) have died off and are now washing up on shore. Aphanizomenon colonies sitll fairly abundant. Waterfowl are still on the lake. Leah was a trooper to row the boat in the cold today! (Collection was a composite of grab samples). Microcstin ID M190206. Probe 47482.Tow Net.

GPS: 55.23231. -113.28538. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.1-0.3 m. Jack and pickerel and perch. pelicans and ducks. Very limited activity. 0.1-2.5 on DIL163. Rest on CAL166. Sun came out around noon. 2-3 fishing boats. Probe didn't read 0.1 m depth. Microcystin ID: M190065. Probe 60443. Tow Net. Tow Net.

GPS: 55.22801. -113.28523. Wind Speed: 15-25 kmh. Wind Dir: W/SW. Waves: 0.5-0.7 m. Pelicans. 1 other boat on water. Clouds broke about 10:30 MST. Fair amoutn of round floaty in column. Reading at 17.5 m may have been on bottom slightly. Microcystin ID M190200. Probe Number 60443. Tow Net.

GPS: 55.23312. -113.29218. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: N/NE. Waves 0.2 m. Pelicans and gulls. 1 fishing boat. 1 water skiing. zoonet has a hole in basket/tube/net. Brief but strong fishy smell between points 2 and three. Tow net. Microcystin ID m190201. Probe 60443.

Wind Speed: 15-5 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.2 m. Very foggy in morning, also very windy in morning. wind calmed and cleared over the day. Rick badry drove, sherman mitchell. Plantothrix bloom. 14 m zoo haul.

GPS: 51.03299. -113.81271. Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0.2 m. Stormy but superisingly low wind and no rain at sampling time. Weed clipping tractor things in North by the bridge.Wisconsin Net . Microcystin ID M190128. Probe 62891.

GPS: 51.03349. -113.81315. Wind Speed: 8 kmh. Wind Dir: SE. Waves: 0.2 m. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190129. Probe 62897. Lots of wakeboard water skiiers making waves. Beautiful and sunny. Weed boat out collecting/cutting. DO Calibration mon July 22 failed (last cal Fri July 12).
GPS: 51.03325. -113.81297. Wind Speed: 15 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0.2 m. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190127. Probe 62897. Windy. Weed cutters. Sailers out. QC Sample 19SWE06652 Speck Lake
GPS: 51.03342. -113.81284. Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.2 m. Microcystin M190126. Probe 62897. Tow Net.

GPS: 52.5775. -110.006. Wind Speed: 10-20 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.1-0.2 m. Lots of birds. Perch. 3 fishing boats. 1 canoe. stocked with trainbow trout. fish jumping. wind kept coming and going. no known fish kills. probe didn't read 0.1 m depth. estimated and recorded on probe. Tow net. Microcystin ID M190187. Probe 60443.

GPS: 52.57768. -110.00590. Wind Speed: 20-30 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.2 m. Wakeboarders, water skiiers, fishing, paddle boarding. fairly windy. lots of drift. depth finder didn't work. locations of site 8&9 tough to find. AIS @ Comp sites 1,2,9. Microcystin ID M190188. Tow Net. Probe 60443.

GPS: 52.57787. -110.00565. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: E/NE. Waves: 0-0.5 m. Tow net. Microcystin ID: M190189. Probe Number 60443. Rained pretty well all night prior. Grebes, ducks.  2 fishing boats. fishing from dock. less fish jumping.

GPS: 52.57740. -110.00619. Wind Speed: 21 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.01 m. Overcast nad a little windy on the water today. Lots of sand along edge of the lake, and the lake as well has a sandy bottom. Water levels are up today. Although wind was a litle high today, the lake is fairly sheltered. Many comp sites were reading 11-13 m. although profile site is only ~10 m. Very shallow sandbar in the middle of the lake. Zach was the conservation officer today. Microcystin ID: M190190. Probe 62091.

SampleComment: GPS: 49.668. -110.291. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0.05 m. Real windy yesterday. Boat driver CO Darwyn. Leopard frog egg masses, pied billed grebe, horned grebe, white pelicans. Dead fish (30 cm). 1 haul at each site, some very shallow. did a grab sample @ 2 comp sites. Microcystin ID M190183. Wisconsin Net. Probe 62897.
Terns, tree swallows, turkey vulture. Way more weeds than in June. Tow net. Probe 62897. Microcystin ID M190182.
Wind Speed: 15 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0 m. Water skiier, lots of weeds. Tow net. Microcystin ID M190186. Probe 62897. QC Sample 19SWE06610 Earwyn Lake
GPS: 49.66753. -110.28984. Wind Speed 6 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.2 m. Microcystin ID M190184. Probe 62897. Tow Net. Zoop to 7 m.
Some drifting macrophytes in the middle of the lake. Depth not working on sonde (used tape and weight to confirm depths). Color, turbidity and odor observation not recorded
Dispersed colonial cyanobacteria. Water flowing out the outflow over the weir.
Foggy. Aphan algae, brown. Surface, Bttm and field blank collected for Hg and Metals. Color, turbidity and odor observation not recorded
Aphan visible in water column. Overcast and calm. Recent rain in area
no redox recorded

GPS: 53.46084. -113.09038. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: SW. Waves: 0.05 m. Wisconsin Net. Prbe 60451. Microcystin M190207. Overcast day, with slight wind every so often. Lake water visually turbid, but no visual evidence of algal bloom. Volunteer concerned about cows accessing lake this year, on north west end. Cormorant spotted. Minimal new development on the shore this year. Just one clear uct lot, being developed for dock. Fox family lives under shed.

GPS: 53.46084. -113.09038. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.01 m. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190208. Probe 60451. Very calm day. Water very clear at Richard's Dock. Brad and Jenny Pham aided in sampling today. Lots of zooplankton ; pigmented (red) and lots of ephippia. Red grebe, blue heron spotted. People water skiing. AIS mussel samples collected along deep plateau; no public access, but a lot of residents have power boats. milfoil collected from western point.

GPS: 53.46084. -113.09038. Wind Speed: 11kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.03 m. Tow Net. Very cold and windy day. Two anchors used to hold in plaec at the profile and mussel veliger sampling sites. Algal bloom at the lake. ph profile interesting. QZ sample collected, and mussel samples for AIS also collected. Richard said that levels were so high that the outlet stream mightstart to run Grebes spotted again. Microcystin ID M190209. Probe 62841 QC Normandeau Lake 19SWE03883

GPS: 53.46884. -113.09038. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.03 m. Calm and fully overcast day. Yesterday was very windy, and last two days were very sunny. suspended algal colonies very dense, but no surface scum or surface layer of algae. Redox values may be off - will re-calibrate probe. Richard wants half moon to be sampled next year. Tow net Microcystin ID M190210. Tow Net. Probe 62891. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 53.43. -114.25658. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.01 m. Practice sampling day with new staff. Trina is the driver. Very calm day, not a lot of water traffic. Spotted a pair of loons at the boat launch. Tow Net. No water chemistry submitted - only a profile.

GPS: 54.07882. -110.90926. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: SE. Waves: 0.01 m. Very hot and calm afternoon for sampling. Wate rwas green, but large cyanobacterial colonies were not visible. Paul Kip was the volunteer. AIS veliger samples taken at profile, pp boat lauch, and southeast campground. Milfoil collected on east shore just north of the provincial park at a reed bed. Lake very busy in the evening with recreational and fishing boats. Microcystin ID M190174. Probe 62891. Tow net.

GPS: 54.07882. -110.90926. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.05 m. Very sunny day, with a slight wind. Warmed up substantially as the day progressed. Paul Kip was the volunteer today - sampling was very efficient. Water was darkish green, but no visible particles/cyanobacteria colonies in the water. Divers were working on the new water treatment plant for the Kehewin Reserve. Mussel veliger samples taken at the same locations - the profile, provincial park boat launch, and southern campground. M190175. Tow. Probe 62891 QC Sample 19SWE04052 Ken Lake.

GPS: 54.07882. -110.90926. Wind Speed 10 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.02 m. Overcast, and coldday. Water relatively calm, and lake not busy at all. Did I mention earlier that divers are working on the new water treatment plant? Paul Kip was the volunteer, and he brought out his dog Trapper. Today was sampling with a new probe, although the redox values look a little suspicious. A metals sample was collected at the profile site (19SWE04154). Probe 47482. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190176. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54.07882. -110.90926. Wind Speed: 16 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.03 m. Windy day, quite wavy in the north part of th elake (while the south part near the boat launch was quite protected). Lake water looked mainly brown, but green when Secchi disk was lowered, and also from the zooplankton sample. Lake appeared to be very oxygenated. Spotted a bald eagle. Microcystin ID M190177. Tow Net. Probe 47482. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.
Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 52.43237. -113.79808. Wind Speed: 15 kmh. Wind Dir: W/NW. Waves: 0.1 m. 3 hauls/site. Pelicans, loons, swallows. Lots of yellow pond lily on edges. flowering. Noone on the water. Gusty wind to 25 kmh. Lots of visible submerged veg. Chara, richardson PW, stuckenia spp. Microcystin ID M190191. Probe 60443. Tow Net.

GPS: 52.43193. -113.79800. Wind Speed: 15 kmh. Wind Dir: S/SE. Waves: 0.1 m. Rowers on water. Loons heard and seen. Grebes. Did not sample site 7. Too much veg. AIS @ composite 1, 6, 4. Site 9 shifted south. Too much chara. 3xhauls/site. May need more next time. Microcystin ID M190192. Probe 60443. Tow net.

GPS: 52.43255. -113.79730. Wind: 20-8 kmh. Wind Dir: SE. Waves: 0.2 m. pH Reading issues. skipped pt 7 due to veg. wind died down huge. lots of very small fish. loons and grebes. 3 hauls per site. Tow net. Probe 60443. Microcystin M190193. QC Sample 19SWE05649 Anto Lake.
Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0.05 m. Tow net. Lots of gulls. Cloud not access comp sites 6 and 7 due to chara growth. 3 tube hauls per site. Microcystin ID M190194.

Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: NE. Waves: 0.05 m. Bev's bay had high waves, but the rest of Laurier wasn't too choppy. bev's bay was thick with cyanobacteria (thanks to wind direction) but the bloom was prevalent across the whole lake. Water levels still high - lots of water lapping near houses and uplawns. large groups of cormorants, flying overhead. Pelicans also spotted. One bald eagle was spotted hunting on the north end. Probe 6051. Microcystin ID M190150. Wisconsin Net.

GPS: 53.85847. -110.50676. Wind Speed: 8 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.05 m. Tow Net. Probe 62891. Microcystin ID M190151. Storm and rain the night before; foggy morning, but by the end of sampling the clouds broke. bloom still in full force, with cyanobacteria now clumping. Gleotrichia identified from zooplankton haul sample. First sampling with new composit esite locations (moved a site from the south of the lake to the now accessible west bay). Duckweed also dispersed throughout the lake - could be flowing in from Whitney Lake inflow @ west bay. Many grebes and pelicans. No milfoil identified at 4 location checked across the lake. AIS veliger samples taken at profile, and near each boat launch (south and west). Probe 62891. Microcystin ID M190151. Tow Net.
Missed Trip - Volunteer Unavailable

GPS: 53.85847. -110.50676. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.01 m.Very beautiful and calm day. Brad P helped with sampling today. Lake levels are still very high. Cyanobacteria levels were high, and were clumping all across lake, and even formed streaks in some locations> Duck weed also ery prevalent. Metal sample taken (19swe04082). Mussel veligers monitoring done as well - same location as July (profile south boat launch and west boat launch). Probe 62891. Microcystin ID M190152. Tow Net. Bev Lake QC 19SWE04080. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: S/SE. Waves: 0.1 m. Wisconsin Net. Prbe 62897. Microcystin ID M190110. Loons, lots of gulls. Lots of invert larvae (unknown spp). Weeds, shallow, silty and black. particles. small evidence of blooms? All grabs for composite.
GPS: 52.76878. -112.97986. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: W/NW. Waves: 0.1 m. Many seagulls, really calm. 500 ml grabs at sites. Tow Net. Probe 62897. Microcystin ID M190111.
GPS: 52.46714. -112.88286. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: S/SW. Waves: 0.1 m. Green!. Probe 62897. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190108. QC Sample 19SWE06708 Doug Lake.
GPS: 52.77041. -112.97965. Wind Speed: 18 kmh. Wind Dir: W/NW. Waves: 0.1 m. Tow Net. Probe 62897. Microcystin ID M190109. Windy, got very gusty around the 8th sample!.

windy, big waves, east side of lake full of blue greens. foam 1 foot high on shoreline, smells like algae. battery on light meter died. No bottom WQ sample collected because lake wasn't stratified.

GPS: 54.612. -110.286. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.07 m. It was raining when the sampling began, but then the rain tapered off after profile sampling was finished. Wind started blowing from the W, but by the end of sampling it was blaring from the SE. Volunteer mentiond recent spike in arsenic, conerned about metal concentrations. Little shoreline development. Loons, odonates, and deer spotted. Probe 60451. Microcystin ID M190178. Wisconsin Net.

Beautiful day, possibly a tad windy. (wind picked up throughout sampling). Dean wood was the volunteer today; the pontoon he borrows wasn't running so we borrowed his neighbours (steve). veliger ais samples taken at profile (near den's subdivision). near camping society & boat launch, and near another subdivision and campground (shelter bay). 10 m samples for composites, although euphotic depth was 11.0 m. (only had a 10 m tube). Water very clear across whole lake. Water levels apparently up relative to normal. I checked for milfoil at northwest area of lake near Marie creek inflow and at the outflow in the southewest bay. No milfoil. Julian date on the file name should've been 193. Saw a beautiful osprey!. Probe 60451. Microcystin ID M190179. Tow Net.

GPS: 54.61251. -110.28600. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: SW. Waves: 0.05 m. Cold day with light rain and mist. Very calm water. Dean wood was the volunteer and said the water levels have com eup a foot from July. Metal sample taken at profil e(19swe03905) important because residents are concerned about metal level increases observed from the 2016 sampling. Mussel veliger samples taken at same sites as July (profile, campling society, and nera Shelter Bay. QC sample poured off as well.). An osprey, loons, and grebes were spotted. Dean's partner Pam used to do aquatics and fisheries sampling in Ontario. Probe 62891. M190180. Tow Net. QC Sample 19swe03903 Dean Lake.

GPS: 54.61251. -110.28600. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: S. Waves: 0.05 m. Overcast, but fairly calm day. Paul Kip was the volunteer, and we launched from the Marie Lake campling society boat laumnch. The secchi was surprisingly shallow, but could've been hard to measure since the water was fairly wavey. But the zooplankton haul was fairly green as well. Very mixed oxygenated. Fish finder found many fish. Tow Net. Microcystin ID M190181. Probe 47482.
Surface grab for metals

GPS: 54.28777. -111.10362. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.05 m. Wisconsin. Probe 60451. microcystin ID M190067. Metalimnetic bloom detected at 4.5-4.7 m. Kemmerer samples taken. Cows access the lake on the northwest end. Blue heron, loon, red-neck grebe, pelican spotted. Southwest end (by the boat launch) had wash-up of algae. interesting oxygen and pH profiles. Garry and Nadine were the volunteers, and Caitlin helped with sampling. Ambert , rolf phyto samples, microcystin samples, sent off for metalimnetic bloom grab. Microcystin ID M190158. Probe 60451. Wisconsin.

GPS: 54.28777. -111.10362. Wind Speed: 8 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.05 m. Very calm and sunny morning. Garry and nadine volunteered, and their friend heather came along. First lake sampled with new multiprobe (since old one, pH probe was dying). Although oxygen levels increased in the epilimnion, a metalimnetic increase in oxygen was observed, like the June sampling. Kemmerer sample taken @ 3.0 m; planktothrix sp. in lower abundance relative to June sampling, and zooplankton haul revealed it to be brown in colour, instead of pink like before. AIS veliger samples tkaen @ profile and two deep spots near the boat launch. Loons on lake!. Microcystin ID M190159. Probe 62891. Tow Net. A phyto, amber phyto, and microcystin sample were taken at the metalimnion. Microcystin metalimnion sample ID M190199.

GPS: 54.28777. -111.10362. Wind Speed: 19 kmh. Wind Dir: SW. Waves: 0.05 m. Tow Net. Probe 62891. Microcystin ID M190160. Wind picked up in the afternoon ; hard to stay steady at the profile spot. Garry (I didn't know it was spelt with 2 r's), Nadine, 2 friends, and 3 grandkids were all aboard today. No evidence of a metalimnetic bloom from the oxygen readings, or from the zooplankton haul. Metal sample taken (19SWE 03991) QC taken, and AIS veliger sample taken at profile and two more sites near the boat launch. garry and his friends onboard might buy farmland that backs onto the lake toward the west shore - they hav ea hack to bypass the riparian easement, they were cautioned then about shoreline development. Microcystin ID M190160. Probe 62891. Tow Net. QC Sample 19SWE03989 Gary Lake. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54.52188. -110.49820. Wind Speed: 8 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.05 m. Very calm conditions when sampling began. water clarity on dock was very good. Pelicans on th ewater, and apparently moose have raised their young on the island. (very thick forest on island). Area around Crane Lake has not seen a fire in over 100 yrs. So forest is very dense mixed wood, with tall white spruce. Natural beaches along the shore. Many odonates, shoreline sparsely popualted. Ron Young is the volunteer. Wisconsin Net. Microcystin ID M190162. Probe Number 60451

GPS: 54.52188. -110.49820. Wind Speed: 5 kmh. Wind Dir: SW. Waves: 0.05 m. Very calm when sampling began. Started cloudy. Then the clouds broke and hour into sampling. Prior to sampling, ron young had heard report sof a green slime in the north skiers bay. one hypothesis was a metalimnetic bloomc ome to the surface, but there was no O2 spike at th emetalimnion. Upon inspecting th eskiers bay, clumps of benthic algae were seen floating in low density and washed up in the reeds, near shore. A benthic algae release was the other hypothesis, this apperas to be the case since the bay is shallow, and has lots of benthic algae growing on submerged macrophytes. Milfoil was also collected from this bay. AIS veliger samples @ profile and the two boat launches. Microcystin ID M190163. Probe 60481. Tow Net.

GPS: 54.52188. -110.49820. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: SW. Waves: 0.01 m. Very calm morning, almost glass. Perfect secchi depth reading conditions (usually they're not this good, so this secchi depth may be skewed deeper than other lake of comparable water clarity, but more difficult secchi depth measurement conditions. Metals sample taken @ profile (19swe03949). AIS Veliger hauls taken at some locations - profile, and both boat launches. Some larger algal filaments observed from the zooplankton haul water sample. QC taken as well. Large group of loons spotted (maybe 10). A few black bears in the area. Microcysitn ID M190164. Tow Net. GPS 54.52188, -110.49820. QC 19SWE03947 Ron Lake. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54.52188. -110.49820. Wind Speed: 21 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.1 m. Quite windy today, a lot of foam streaks on the water's surface. Leaves were beautiful and yellow. Apparently many blackbears in the area this year. Secchi depth was difficult to measure becase of the waves. Likely a little deeper (clearer). Depth probe was not very stable (probe is getting old).

SampleComment: GPS: 54.240. -110.909. Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.01 m. Wisconsin. M190166. Probe 60451. Very calm day, and hot. Water levels higher compared to other lakes in region. Certain areas of shoreline have extensive development, right to shoreline. Volunteer concerned about garbage in water, and residents general knowledge about nurtient runoff and riparian are imporant. Fish jumping (couldn't see which species).

GPS: 54.23983. -110.91019. Wind Speed: 14 kmh. Wind Dir: N. Waves: 0.05 m. A little windy, wavey and cloudy when sampling started ,but towards the end of sampling the lcouds and wind broke nad water became very calm. mark's father in law Murray was the volunteer today - he has a place on crane lake. water failry clear, some colonies of aphanizomenon at profile site. Then at franchere bay, the pahanizmonen colonies were blooming, and even clumping. Then to the northwest Vezuea Bay was extremely clear, no cyanobacterial colonies. After inspecting water, Gleotrichia may also be in high abundance. AIS mussel hauls at profile, franchere bay, and vezeau bay deep hole. Tow net. Probe 60451. Microcystin ID M190167.

GPS: 54.2400. -110.90900. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0 m. very hot and calm day. cyanobacteria definitely exhibiting their buoyancy control - even streaks on the water in some areas. Bloom greatest in the west (franchere bay) and least in east (Vezeau Bay). Mark Fieger was the volunteer - said he wants to run for MD council and push for lake management. Mussel samples, taken at same three locations as July. Total recoverable metals grab sample taken at profile (19swe03845) QC sample also collected. Microcystin ID M190168. Probe 62891. Tow Net.QC Sample Mark Lake 19SWE03842.

GPS: 54.23983. -110.91019. Wind Speed: 3 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0 m. Very calm and beautiful day to sample. Leaves just changing and lake was not very busy at all. mark fieger was the volunteer today and Harnoor helped with sampling today. Water levels were slightly down compared to the rest of the season. Water clarity still poor. Bloom just beginning to degrade and mix throughout the water column. Geese were starting to fly south. Mark mentioned some controvesy over weir opposition. Tow Net. Probe 47482. Microcystin M190169. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.
Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54.12889. -110.64364. Wind Speed: 18 kmh. Wind Dir: NE. Waves: 0.01 m. Wisconsin Net. Probe 60451. Microcystin ID M190170. Windy start of the day. Then wind calmed down right after profile sampling. Sun out (50%) for about an hour mid-way. No fish, cormorants out, nesting in numerous boulder bars. Last recorded depth was likely the bottom (why no sample code is assigned). Light penetration to bottom throughout the lake.

GPS: 54.12310. -110.64599. Wind Speed: 20 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.25 m. Tow Net. Probe 60451. Microcystin ID M190171. Very windy day, waves especially large at SE of the lake. Prior storms may have moved a lot of sediment to the profile site, making profile more shallow than in June (profile in SE). AIS mussel veliger sample taken at profile, northwest near Spring Beach. Most developed Area. And central west of the lake. A lot of cormorants, some pelicans. High waves and storm rolling in forced us to miss one site (the centre of the lake).

GPS: 54.12310. -110.64599. Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.05 m. Very wavy again, with amny surface foams. AIS mussel samples collected at same locations as July, metal  sample (19SWE03873) collected at profile, QC sample taken, and milfoil was searched for along eastern shore and south west bay, but not spotted. Many cormorants and pelicans live on the many rock isalnds of the lake. Sandpiper also spotted. Probe 62891. Microcystin ID M190172. Tow Net. 19SWE03871. Bourgeois Lake QC.

GPS: 54.12310. -110.64599. Wind Speed: 15 kmh. Wind Dir; W. Waves: 0.4 m. Very windy day, but sunny the entire sampling. A lot of surface foam. Many pelicans, grebes, cormorants, canada geese, and other water fowl. Redox oddly negative? Sample with Jeff H and Richard B. Water only seeemd green while measuring Secchi, and in the shallows. Lake will be sampled for oxygen throughout winter. Would like to sample again in two years. Microcystin ID M190173. Probe 62841. Tow Net. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.
Forest fire smoke in the air.  Lake surface is littered with tree fluff, floating macrophytes, and organic debris. ChlA readings were rapidly changing +/- 50%. grab at 1m and at 7m.
Rain at time of sample. Very windy in recent days. Lake is mixed, no bottom grab. Large fluctuation in light during light profile.Grab with Van Dorne at 1m.
increasing wind and cloud. changed out weather station on buoy for new unti 1500-1610. top grab 1m, bottom grab 7m.

last depth at 8.0m metres hit the bottom. Sunny, light wind. Precipitation gauge, and other gauges on top of the buoy are all clear of debris. All gauges were wiped anyways. Photos taken.  No chl a sensor on sonde. Lake nakamun zooplankton sample preserved with isopropyl alcohol instead of formalin. Identification of invertebrates may be difficult.
No comments/observations recorded regarding lake conditions. Water column is not stratified; no bottom sample collected
boat issues, lake partially frozen, composite collection not possible. No duplicate, field blank, or turbidity samples. No veligers.
10 cm water on top of ice. Sample collected with peristaltic pump and hose and by Teflon Kemerrer.

GPS: 54.14505. -111.50199. Wind Speed: 11 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.01 m. Sunny day with low wind. Algal bloom of some sort in Christy's Basin (Aphanizomenon?) Diversity of avian life (birds, and ducks). Many more islands than the bath map showed. Reox @ 5.5 m. unreliable, since bottom was hit before measruement collection). Once wind picked up, the algal bloom dispersed to deeper depths. Microcystin ID M 190211. Probe 60451. Wisconsin Net.

GPS: 54.14505. -111.50199. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: NW. Waves: 0.03 m. Tow net. Microcystin ID M190212. Probe 60451. Very sunny and calm day. Charity drove the boat today, and Tatiana came along as well. Right away, we noticed that the bloom obvserved in June had decreased, and the Secchi, also confirmed clearer water in the main basin. Some other bays still had relatively thick blooms. Some pelicans spotted. AIS mussel samples taken @ profile, entrance to north developed bay, 4.5 m sampling depth (but varied because lake was very shallow. Oxygen measurement was validated post sampling - probe deemed to be operating properly. Microcysitn ID M190212. Probe 60451. Tow Net.

GPS: 54.14505. -111.50199. Wind Speed: 6 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0 m. Very calm sampling conditions. Bloom looks to have decreased slightly, but no signs of senescence. QZ Sample taken, and AIS veliger sample taken at same locations as July. Algal bloom looks to be primarily Aphanizomenon colonies, perhaps other filamentous species as well. Many waterfowl on the lake (including lots of pelicans). Euphotic tubing hit bottom while sampling - rinsed as well and as thoroughly as possible. Microcystin ID M190213. Probe 62891. Tow net. QC Sample 19SWE04021 Charity Lake. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54. 11263. -111.34563. Wind Speed: 19 kmh. Wind Dir: E. Waves: 0.2 m. Wisconsin Net. Microcystin ID M190154. Probe 60451. Quite windy when sampling began, then calmed down, then picked up again towards the end of sampling. White streaks on the water from previous whitecaps - patrick said it was very windy in the morning. foam on shoreline. suspended algal colonies, submergent weeds close to some of the islands. Cormorants, gulls, pelicans spotted. 6.5 m measurement likely interaction with stirred up sediments. Microcystin ID M190154. Probe 60451. Wisconsin.

GPS: 54.11263. -111.34563. Very calm day. cyanobacteria definitely were rising to the surface. AIS veliger samples taken at profile, northeast campground, and at west boat launch. Milfoil found and collected. Patrick Traudt was the volunteer today. Apparently, there are garter snakes that hang out at Patrick's place. Tow net. Microcystin ID M190155. Probe 62891.

GPS: 54.11263. -111.34563. Wind Speed: 10 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.03 m. Degrading surface scums of cyanobacteria (bright blue) all along the shore of Horsehshoe bay. It stunk. Day started out hot and relatively calm, and then it clouded over and got a tad windier. Water very green - mainly aphanizomenon and other filamnetous cyanobacteria. Fewer birds today compared to last samplings. AIS veliger samples taken at same locations as July QC sample taken, and  ametals sample as well. 19SWE04038. Tow net. Microcystin M190156. Probe 62891. QC Sample Patrick Lake 19SWE04036. Redox not available due to malfunctioning equipment.

GPS: 54.11263. -111.34563. Wind Speed: 16 kmh. Wind Dir: W. Waves: 0.03 m. Fairly windy day. Scums were gone today, but cyanobacteria colonies still present in the water in high abundance. However, they were visibly not as green; they looked more brown (senescing?) Many macrophyte beds near the south end of the lake, and floating milfoil also observed. Patrick has stated many times that the community is not educated in shoreline management. many properties have developed their shorelines very poorly. M190157. Tow Net. Probe 47482.
